# Protected surface — the success-definition surface for {{PROJECT_NAME}}.
#
# Every path here defines what "success" means: the gates, the thresholds,
# the configs, and the floor mechanism itself. Editing any of these requires
# the owner's review via the generated .github/CODEOWNERS.
#
# `sdlc init` fills {{OWNER}}, generates .github/CODEOWNERS, and runs the sync
# test for you. If you copied the harness by hand: replace {{OWNER}}, then run
#   python scripts/gen_codeowners.py   (writes .github/CODEOWNERS)
# and commit protected-surface.txt AND .github/CODEOWNERS together.
#
# A sync test (tests/test_protected_surface_sync.py) and the structural-floor
# CI gate fail the build if the two ever drift apart — so the success-
# definition surface cannot be quietly relocated to pass.

# default-owner: {{OWNER}}

# — Quality Gate config (the bar: rules, PRS weights, thresholds)
.quality-gate.json

# — Cathedral Keeper config (enabled policies, severities, QG wiring)
.cathedral-keeper.json

# — The vendored QG+CK engines themselves: read-only by convention, and any
#   edit (which could weaken the gates) requires the owner's review. Drift
#   detection against the manifest's per-file sha256 record is `sdlc status`.
tools/qa/

# — CI gate definitions
.github/workflows/

# — Agent operating contract + session machinery: tampering here could
#   silently weaken the gates or disable the session-memory receipts layer.
CLAUDE.md
.claude/settings.json

# — The structural floor itself (keep these — the mechanism protects itself)
protected-surface.txt
.github/CODEOWNERS
scripts/gen_codeowners.py
